{
  "model": "unknown",
  "total_claims": 52,
  "claims": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "text": "We assume spherical symmetry.",
      "type": "assumption",
      "provenance": "asserted",
      "depends_on": [],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "We assume static spacetime (time-independent, non-rotating).",
      "type": "assumption",
      "provenance": "asserted",
      "depends_on": [],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "We assume vacuum outside the mass, so T_{\u03bc\u03bd}=0.",
      "type": "assumption",
      "provenance": "asserted",
      "depends_on": [],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "Einstein's equations reduce to R_{\u03bc\u03bd}=0 since G_{\u03bc\u03bd}=R_{\u03bc\u03bd}-\u00bdg_{\u03bc\u03bd}R=0.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        3
      ],
      "notes": "Requires taking trace to show R=0 first; step is compressed but correct."
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "The most general static, spherically symmetric line element in coordinates (t,r,\u03b8,\u03c6) can be written as ds\u00b2=-e^{2\u03a6(r)}c\u00b2dt\u00b2+e^{2\u039b(r)}dr\u00b2+r\u00b2d\u03b8\u00b2+r\u00b2sin\u00b2\u03b8 d\u03c6\u00b2.",
      "type": "invocation_of_known_result",
      "provenance": "cited",
      "depends_on": [
        1,
        2
      ],
      "notes": "Standard result; cross terms can be eliminated by coordinate choice."
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "text": "The metric is diagonal with g_{tt}=-e^{2\u03a6}c\u00b2, g_{rr}=e^{2\u039b}, g_{\u03b8\u03b8}=r\u00b2, g_{\u03c6\u03c6}=r\u00b2sin\u00b2\u03b8.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        5
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 7,
      "text": "The inverse metric has g^{tt}=-e^{-2\u03a6}/c\u00b2, g^{rr}=e^{-2\u039b}, g^{\u03b8\u03b8}=1/r\u00b2, g^{\u03c6\u03c6}=1/(r\u00b2sin\u00b2\u03b8).",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        6
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 8,
      "text": "The nontrivial Ricci tensor components are R_{tt}=0, R_{rr}=0, R_{\u03b8\u03b8}=0, with R_{\u03c6\u03c6}=sin\u00b2\u03b8 R_{\u03b8\u03b8}.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        4,
        6
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 9,
      "text": "R_{tt}=e^{2(\u03a6-\u039b)}c\u00b2(\u03a6''+\u03a6'\u00b2-\u03a6'\u039b'+2\u03a6'/r)=0.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        6,
        7,
        8
      ],
      "notes": "Standard Ricci component for this ansatz; computation omitted."
    },
    {
      "id": 10,
      "text": "R_{rr}=-\u03a6''-\u03a6'\u00b2+\u03a6'\u039b'+2\u039b'/r=0.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        6,
        7,
        8
      ],
      "notes": "Standard Ricci component for this ansatz; computation omitted."
    },
    {
      "id": 11,
      "text": "R_{\u03b8\u03b8}=1-e^{-2\u039b}(1-r\u039b'+r\u03a6')=0.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        6,
        7,
        8
      ],
      "notes": "Standard Ricci component for this ansatz; computation omitted."
    },
    {
      "id": 12,
      "text": "Primes denote derivatives with respect to r.",
      "type": "definition",
      "provenance": "asserted",
      "depends_on": [],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 13,
      "text": "From R_{tt}=0: \u03a6''+\u03a6'\u00b2-\u03a6'\u039b'+2\u03a6'/r=0.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        9
      ],
      "notes": "Dividing out the prefactor e^{2(\u03a6-\u039b)}c\u00b2."
    },
    {
      "id": 14,
      "text": "From R_{rr}=0: -\u03a6''-\u03a6'\u00b2+\u03a6'\u039b'+2\u039b'/r=0.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        10
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 15,
      "text": "Adding the equations from R_{tt}=0 and R_{rr}=0 gives (2/r)(\u03a6'+\u039b')=0.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        13,
        14
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 16,
      "text": "Hence \u03a6'+\u039b'=0, so \u03a6(r)=-\u039b(r)+const.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        15
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 17,
      "text": "The constant can be absorbed into a rescaling of the time coordinate t, so we take \u03a6(r)=-\u039b(r).",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "asserted",
      "depends_on": [
        16
      ],
      "notes": "Standard coordinate freedom argument."
    },
    {
      "id": 18,
      "text": "Thus e^{2\u03a6}=e^{-2\u039b}.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        17
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 19,
      "text": "Let f(r)\u2261e^{2\u03a6(r)}=e^{-2\u039b(r)}.",
      "type": "definition",
      "provenance": "asserted",
      "depends_on": [
        18
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 20,
      "text": "The metric becomes ds\u00b2=-f(r)c\u00b2dt\u00b2+dr\u00b2/f(r)+r\u00b2d\u03a9\u00b2, where d\u03a9\u00b2=d\u03b8\u00b2+sin\u00b2\u03b8 d\u03c6\u00b2.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        5,
        19
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 21,
      "text": "Using R_{\u03b8\u03b8}=0: 1-e^{-2\u039b}(1-r\u039b'+r\u03a6')=0.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        11
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 22,
      "text": "Since \u03a6'=-\u039b', we have 1-r\u039b'+r\u03a6'=1-2r\u039b'.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        17,
        21
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 23,
      "text": "Also e^{-2\u039b}=f(r).",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        19
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 24,
      "text": "So R_{\u03b8\u03b8}=0 becomes 1-f(r)(1-2r\u039b')=0.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        21,
        22,
        23
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 25,
      "text": "Since f=e^{-2\u039b}, differentiating gives f'=-2\u039b'e^{-2\u039b}=-2\u039b'f.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        19
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 26,
      "text": "Hence \u039b'=-f'/(2f).",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        25
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 27,
      "text": "Substituting into R_{\u03b8\u03b8}=0: 1-f(1+rf'/f)=0.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        24,
        26
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 28,
      "text": "This simplifies to 1-f-rf'=0.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        27
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 29,
      "text": "Thus rf'+f=1, which is d/dr(rf)=1.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        28
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 30,
      "text": "Integrating gives rf=r+C, where C is an integration constant.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        29
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 31,
      "text": "Therefore f(r)=1+C/r.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        30
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 32,
      "text": "The metric is ds\u00b2=-(1+C/r)c\u00b2dt\u00b2+dr\u00b2/(1+C/r)+r\u00b2d\u03a9\u00b2.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        20,
        31
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 33,
      "text": "Far from the mass, spacetime must approach flat Minkowski space, so f(r)\u21921 as r\u2192\u221e.",
      "type": "assumption",
      "provenance": "asserted",
      "depends_on": [],
      "notes": "Asymptotic flatness boundary condition."
    },
    {
      "id": 34,
      "text": "The form f(r)=1+C/r already satisfies f(r)\u21921 as r\u2192\u221e.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        31,
        33
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 35,
      "text": "In the weak-field Newtonian limit, g_{tt}\u2248-(1+2\u03c6_N/c\u00b2), where \u03c6_N is the Newtonian potential.",
      "type": "invocation_of_known_result",
      "provenance": "cited",
      "depends_on": [],
      "notes": "Standard weak-field limit of GR."
    },
    {
      "id": 36,
      "text": "The Newtonian potential outside a mass M is \u03c6_N(r)=-GM/r.",
      "type": "invocation_of_known_result",
      "provenance": "cited",
      "depends_on": [],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 37,
      "text": "From the metric, g_{tt}/c\u00b2=-(1+C/r).",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        32
      ],
      "notes": "Model writes g_{tt}=-f(r)c\u00b2dt\u00b2, seems to mean the coefficient."
    },
    {
      "id": 38,
      "text": "In the weak field, 1+C/r=1+2\u03c6_N/c\u00b2=1-2GM/(c\u00b2r).",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        35,
        36,
        37
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 39,
      "text": "Hence C=-2GM/c\u00b2.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        38
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 40,
      "text": "Therefore f(r)=1-2GM/(c\u00b2r).",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        31,
        39
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 41,
      "text": "The Schwarzschild metric is ds\u00b2=-(1-2GM/(c\u00b2r))c\u00b2dt\u00b2+dr\u00b2/(1-2GM/(c\u00b2r))+r\u00b2(d\u03b8\u00b2+sin\u00b2\u03b8 d\u03c6\u00b2).",
      "type": "numerical_result",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        20,
        40
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 42,
      "text": "This is the unique static, spherically symmetric vacuum solution: Birkhoff's theorem guarantees this.",
      "type": "invocation_of_known_result",
      "provenance": "cited",
      "depends_on": [
        41
      ],
      "notes": "Birkhoff's theorem also removes the static assumption."
    },
    {
      "id": 43,
      "text": "The metric coefficients become singular when 1-2GM/(c\u00b2r)=0.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        41
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 44,
      "text": "Solving gives r=2GM/c\u00b2.",
      "type": "numerical_result",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        43
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 45,
      "text": "This defines the Schwarzschild radius: r_s=2GM/c\u00b2.",
      "type": "numerical_result",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        44
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 46,
      "text": "At r=r_s, g_{tt}=0 and g_{rr}\u2192\u221e.",
      "type": "derivation_step",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        41,
        45
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 47,
      "text": "The singularity at r=r_s is a coordinate singularity, not a physical curvature singularity.",
      "type": "physical_interpretation",
      "provenance": "cited",
      "depends_on": [
        45
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 48,
      "text": "The true physical singularity is at r=0.",
      "type": "physical_interpretation",
      "provenance": "cited",
      "depends_on": [],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 49,
      "text": "The Kretschner scalar is K=R_{\u03bc\u03bd\u03c1\u03c3}R^{\u03bc\u03bd\u03c1\u03c3}=48G\u00b2M\u00b2/(c\u2074r\u2076).",
      "type": "invocation_of_known_result",
      "provenance": "cited",
      "depends_on": [
        41
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 50,
      "text": "At r=r_s, the Kretschner scalar is finite; at r=0, it diverges.",
      "type": "physical_interpretation",
      "provenance": "derived",
      "depends_on": [
        45,
        49
      ],
      "notes": "Confirms r_s is coordinate singularity, r=0 is physical."
    },
    {
      "id": 51,
      "text": "The surface r=r_s is the event horizon of a Schwarzschild black hole.",
      "type": "physical_interpretation",
      "provenance": "cited",
      "depends_on": [
        45
      ],
      "notes": ""
    },
    {
      "id": 52,
      "text": "In regular coordinates (e.g. Eddington\u2013Finkelstein or Kruskal\u2013Szekeres), spacetime is smooth at r=r_s.",
      "type": "physical_interpretation",
      "provenance": "cited",
      "depends_on": [
        47,
        51
      ],
      "notes": ""
    }
  ]
}